 the Japanese colonial period (1895–1945), focusing variously on travel writings, Western and Japanese/Oriental-style paintings, architecture, aboriginal material culture, and crafts. Issues addressed include the imagined Taiwan and the "discovery" of the Taiwanese landscape, which developed into the imperial ideology of nangoku (southern country); the problematic idea of "local color," which was imposed by Japanese, and its relation to the "nativism" that was embraced by Taiwanese; the gendered modernity exemplified in the representation of Chinese/Taiwanese women; and the development of Taiwanese artifacts and crafts from colonial to postcolonial times, from their discovery, estheticization, and industrialization to their commodification by both the colonizers and the colonized.Contributors: Chao-Ching Fu, Chia-yu Hu, Yuko Kikuchi, Kaoru Kojima, Ming-chu Lai, Hsin-tien Liao, Naoko Shimazu, Toshio Watanabe, Chuan-ying Yen.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aArt, ChinesexJapanese influences. 0aArt, Chinesey20th century. 0aArt, ChinesezTaiwany20th century. 0aImperialism in art. 7aART / History / Modern (late 19th Century to 1945).2bisacsh1 aFu, Chao-Ching, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHu, Chia-Yu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKikuchi, Yuko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKikuchi, Yuko, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKojima, Kaoru, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLai, Ming-Chu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiao, Hsin-Tien, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShimazu, Naoko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWatanabe, Toshio, ec